{
  "doc_id": "7671",
  "text": "Many of the key findings on animal models have been reproduced in the human heart, but there are some important differences. Both the loss of T-tubule density and flattening of the surface have been demonstrated in cardiomyocytes from the failing human heart using SICM or di-8-ANEPPS staining [CITATION_1] In our study, similar changes were observed in cells from patients with ischaemic, idiopathic dilated, or hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, and were slightly greater in magnitude than alterations seen in the rat MI HF model. Values of the T-tubule index in the failing hearts were close to the 0.25 seen in a similarly mixed population of ischaemic cardiomyopathy, [CITATION_2] idiopathic dilated cardiomyopathy and congenital valvular disease. Hong et al. showed a less organized periodicity of the T-tubule structural protein BIN1 in human failing cardiomyocytes, and also noted a population of shallow (1-2 mm) T-tubules in addition to the sparse elongated ones running into the centre of the cell. [CITATION_3] Dilation of T-tubules and appearance of longitudinal elements (possibly subsarcolemmal and therefore undetectable with surface scanning by SICM) have also been observed. [CITATION_4] The failing human heart is well known for desensitization of the bAR system, independent of aetiology, and it is accepted that there is loss of the b 1 AR with preserved b 2 AR number but b 2 AR 'uncoupling' (now possible to be interpreted as non-cAMP coupling). Signalling partners of the human b 1 -and b 2 ARs differ from those in the rodent heart in a number of respects, which are pertinent to bAR desensitization and compartmentation. Unlike rodent, PDE3 is predominant over PDE4 in the control of cAMP in the failing human heart. 72 -74 Coupling of the b 2 AR to Gi is seen in the normal human atria, [CITATION_5] but there is less evidence for this in ventricular muscle. Although b 2 AR-cAMP-mediated positive inotropism is strongly suppressed by Gi Figure 2 Healthy cardiomyocytes display a defined membrane structure of repeating groove in the z direction. Within these grooves lie the ttubular system which permits a rapid response of the cardiomyocytes to extra-cellular stimuli. Cells from an animal model of chronic heart failure demonstrate a derangement of cellular micro-architecture shown by a loss of repeating z-grooves and disorganized di-8 ANNEPS staining of the sarcolemma. As shown in Figure 1 , b 2 AR-dependent cAMP signals is delocalized in heart failure. By up-regulating SERCA2a in heart failure cells z-groove and sarcolemma staining reveal a healthier phenotype. The b 2 AR-cAMP response is returned to the t-tubular structures (cells from n ¼ 13 animals).",
